They and we are both <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_mammals">mammals,</a> but bunnies are in the order <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagomorpha">Lagomorpha</a> and we aren't.  Clarifying the relationships of the <a href="http://www.colorado.edu/eeb/courses/3770darmstrong/Extended%20Order%20Guide_small.pdf">mammalian orders (pdf)</a> will require more data.  Unlike birds and lizards bunnies are <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synapsids">synapsids</a>.  Recall that early amniotes split into synapsids and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauropsid">sauropsids</a>  (mammal like amniotes and reptile like amniotes). Clearly we mammals and the sauropsids are all <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craniata">craniates.</a>

